i’ve been picking at this new mexico post for quite a while now because it feels like i have so much to say. i want to infuse everything into one succinct blog post but i just can’t do it, so i think for the most part i’m going to stick to the facts here.

i love photographs. the medium is extremely deep and interesting in a philosophical way, but our trip to NM made me think more about life before them. before photographs, humans symbolized through art and writing. before art and writing, we symbolized with language, and before language, speech. modern life can feel to me chillingly symbolic, unreal. i used to feel crushed under the weight of life’s mysteries, but the passage of time, learning, and curiosity have quelled my suffering for now. i take comfort in the fact that this specific type of suffering has a pretty well-defined beginning in terms of human history. symbols have everything to do with the neuroses we present-day humans share with our neolithic brothers and sisters. abstraction is a new thing in the grand scheme, and it comes about at a really interesting time. this is the period in which pastoral life, food storage, art, language, and sedentary communities overtake hunter-gatherer bands. while anthropology fails to determine conclusively why this shift took place, we are feeling the impact of it in every aspect of our lives. staring at my baneful, mismatched food storage containers i am reminded of neolithic pottery and the neurosis which necessitated it at that place and time. carving the patina off desert rocks to symbolize something feels like exactly what i would do as a pastoral ancient guy. i relate so much of my experience of this life to ancient humans. maybe it’s the soul of all things, or something more scientifically cut-and-dry, but the feeling of interconnectedness, the overlay, is the most uncanny thing i know.

anyway, a life without abstraction is almost impossible to imagine. the argument can be made that consciousness itself is a result of abstraction, because “you” only exist as symbol to yourself and others. early symbols however are a brilliant look at life at a certain time and place. through the art historical lens, petroglyph national park is a glorious museum collection. maybe it’s better described as an open studio… 

not long after we stepped off the plane did my sister pick us up and took us out the monument. 

![image](assets/images/newmexico/petro1map.png)

there were tons of little symbols everywhere, all over different rock faces, some only visible in certain angles, apparently only at certain times of day. this one resembled some kind of map to me.

![image](assets/images/newmexico/petro2humanoid.png)

a little phallic flair in this tableau with animals

![image](assets/images/newmexico/petro3glyph.png)

though some were more singular in their symbolism. this one reminds me of a [water glyph](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Water_glyphs).

![image](assets/images/newmexico/petro4humanoid.png)

the grey light made me wonder how many other images were hiding among the rock faces. 

![image](assets/images/newmexico/petro5cat.png)

some depictions felt suspiciously contemporary, but i lack the credentials to back that up empirically.

![image](assets/images/newmexico/petro6assemblage.png)

and some felt really different than the others in terms of artistry, like this assemblage here. i think this one was from another side of the park. 

![image](assets/images/newmexico/petro7hand.png)

and how could you resist a hand print? what a perfect, universal symbol of our shared humanity. it reminds me of being a kid and dipping your hand in paint.

![image](assets/images/newmexico/petro8roadrunner.png)

an enchantingly beautiful roadrunner crossed our paths while we walked along the beatled paths throughout the park.

it was around this time that we came upon a lost pug. 

